Both the columns have proper data entries. No more data normalization is required. We will convert the left out 'day_of_week', 'time' and 'category' columns into numerical form by categorizing the values. The 'time' column can be converted into 'is_AM' and the values can be 1 for 'AM' and 0 for 'PM'.

In [10]:
# Convert time to numerical column with values 0 for AM and 1 for PM
class_data['time'] = class_data['time'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 'AM' else 0)
In [11]:

# Encode the 'category' column
class_data['category'] = label_encoder.fit_transform(class_data['category'])

Distribution of 'days_before':¶

The distribution of this column values could give us information on whether how long the person has stayed as a member of the gym before attending the class affects the percentage.

In [16]:

The distribution shows that people who have attended and not attended classes looks almost the same. This indicates that the 'days_before' column does not act as a deciding factor. We can check which column affects the target variable by plotting out the correlation matrix.

Correlation Matrix:¶

In [17]:
sns.heatmap(class_data.corr(), annot=True, cmap='coolwarm')
plt.show()

The correlation matrix shows that 'months_as_member' column has high positive correlation with the target column 'attended'. This explains that the longer the person has stayed as member of the gym, more the probability of them attending the class. The column 'weight' has the highest negative correlation with the column 'attended' i.e., the lesser the weight of the person, more the probability of them attending the class.

From the two results, we could assume that people who stayed disciplined in attending the gym sessions and saw weight loss are the people who preferred to attend the classes. This means that we should work towards making people interested to attend the gym properly. We could share the weight loss journey of people who have seen visible results to motive the newly joined members. We could make them special offers such as discounts in membership cost when there is seasonal drop in membership count.

Model Training and Evaluation:¶

Training ML model to predict if a person will attend the class or not and target that person will offers and loyalty enhancement program.

In [18]:
X_class = class_data.drop('attended', axis=1)
y_class = class_data['attended']
X_train_class, X_test_class, y_train_class, y_test_class = train_test_split(X_class, y_class, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

Since the data has class imbalance i.e., the class 'not_attended' has twice the number of data compared to class 'attended', we will adjust class weights in the model to refrain from overfitting the model.

In [19]:
from sklearn.utils.class_weight import compute_class_weight

# Compute class weights
class_weights = compute_class_weight(
    class_weight='balanced',
    classes=[0, 1],
    y=y_train_class
)
In [20]:
# Create a dictionary with class weights
class_weight_dict = {0: class_weights[0], 1: class_weights[1]}

Normalizing data using Standard Scaler to feed normalized data into the model:

In [21]:
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_class = scaler.fit_transform(X_train_class)
X_test_class = scaler.transform(X_test_class)

In [22]:

The only column that has to be converted into numerical form here is 'date'. 'month' and 'hour' are already there as separate columns in the data. We need to extract just the 'day' and 'year' details from the 'date' column. We will extract the information and remove the 'date' column from the data.

In [29]:
# Convert 'date' column to datetime, including timezone info
gym_data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(gym_data['date'], format='%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S%z', errors='coerce')

# Convert 'date' column to datetime64[ns] type
gym_data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(gym_data['date'], errors='coerce', utc=True)

# Extract 'day' and 'year' from 'date' column
gym_data['day'] = gym_data['date'].dt.day
gym_data['year'] = gym_data['date'].dt.year.astype(int)

# Drop the 'date' column
gym_data = gym_data.drop(columns=['date'])

The 'timestamp' column is not necessary now since we have 'hour' information. The remaining seconds information is that of a deciding factor for prediction. We can remove it as well.

In [30]:
gym_data = gym_data.drop(columns=['timestamp'])

Based on the month information, we can identify which season of the year it is and based on it, we can guess if more people attend the gym during a season.

In [31]:
gym_data['season'] = gym_data['month'].apply(lambda x: 'Winter' if x in [12, 1, 2] 
                                                    else 'Spring' if x in [3, 4, 5] 
                                                    else 'Summer' if x in [6, 7, 8] 
                                                    else 'Fall')

The column with highest positive correlation is 'hour'. The column with most negative correlation is 'year'. From the data we could say that number of people attending gym increases as the hour of the day increases and has reduced as the year went by. People use the most resources in the later hours of the day. Whatever change the gym went through in the recent years could be the cause for people not attending the gym. With this information, gym institution can make changes to their schedule or manage conducting sessions accordingly.

'temperature' and 'is_during_semester' also are also reasonable deciding factors of the target variable. It means if the temperature is high or during the semester, people tend to attend gym more.

# Calculate the median value of the 'number_people' column
median_count = gym_data['number_people'].median()

Median Number of People: 28.0

The number of people is 0 for most of the days. The median value for it seems to be 28. We will find if the number_people count falls on the greater side of the median value or not. That will be the deciding label for the model. We will train the model to predict whenever the number of people is to be lower than the median count and work towards rectifying it in the gym.

In [37]:
# Create a new column 'above_median' where 1 indicates 'number_people' > median, and 0 otherwise
gym_data['above_median'] = (gym_data['number_people'] > median_count).astype(int)
In [38]:
# Drop the old 'number_people' column if it's no longer needed
gym_data = gym_data.drop(columns=['number_people'])
